### Audit Workflow

When reviewing i18n implementation:

**1. Check for hardcoded strings**

```bash
# Search for hardcoded text patterns
grep -r ">\s*[A-Z]" src/app --include="*.tsx"
# Review results for user-facing text
```

**2. Verify translation file consistency**

```bash
# Compare JSON structures
diff <(jq -S 'keys' src/i18n/messages/en.json) \
     <(jq -S 'keys' src/i18n/messages/de.json)
# Should be identical
```

**3. Check translation hook usage**

```bash
# Find server components using wrong hook
grep -r "useTranslations" src/app --include="*.tsx" -B5 | grep -v "use client"

# Find client components using wrong hook
grep -r "getTranslations" src/app --include="*.tsx" -B5 | grep "use client"
```

**4. Validate locale configuration**

```typescript
// Verify all these match:
// - src/i18n/config.ts: locales array
// - src/proxy.ts: matcher regex
// - src/i18n/messages/: files exist
// - src/app/[locale]/layout.tsx: generateStaticParams
```

### Security & Performance

**Security considerations:**

- Translation values can contain user input in some cases
- Always sanitize dynamic values
- Don't expose sensitive data in translation keys

**Performance tips:**

- Load only needed translations (namespace-based)
- Use static rendering where possible
- Cache translation files
- Consider lazy loading for large translation files

What NOT to Do

Don't use different hooks for server/client
Don't hardcode user-facing strings
Don't create inconsistent JSON structures across locales
Don't forget to update all config files when adding locales
Don't translate technical terms (API, URL, etc.)
Don't include HTML in translation values (use rich text API)
Don't nest locales deeper than necessary (flat is better)

Critical Rules

Always use translation hooks - never hardcode user-facing text
Server uses getTranslations - client uses useTranslations
Identical JSON structure - all locales must have same keys
Complete locale setup - update all 4 required files
Type safety enforced - missing keys cause TypeScript errors
